{
  "text": "The potential therapeutic applications of OPN have been investigated in various pathological contexts, and exogenously administered recombinant OPN protein has been reported to have protective effects in a mouse model of transient focal ischemia [CITATION_1] , in intracerebral hemorrhage mouse model [CITATION_2] , and in animal models of Parkinson' s disease [CITATION_3] , and a neonatal hypoxia-ischemia induced brain injury [CITATION_4] . Recently, we reported recombinant OPN (rOPN) protein had robust neuroprotective effects in the postischemic brain, and that this effect was enhanced by delivering rOPN in biodegradable gelatin microspheres [CITATION_5] . Gilbert [CITATION_6] reported that a 21-amino-acid OPN peptide harboring hydroxyapatite binding domain and a RGD motif mediated α v integrin adhesion in melanoma cells. Furthermore, Doyle [CITATION_7] found that a 20-or even a 10-amino-acid OPN peptide containing the RGD and SLAYGLR motifs had neuroprotective effect in an animal model of transient focal ischemia and Mizuno [CITATION_8] reported a 7-aminoacid OPN peptide harboring the SVVYGLR sequence improved cardiac function in a hamster model of dilated cardiomyopathy. These reports consistently suggest short OPN-derived peptides containing the RGD motif and the SLAYGLR sequence have neuroprotective effects.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "15126150",
    "[CITATION_2]": "853991",
